title: BBC One
description: BBC One offers something of value for everyone with a range of high-quality, popular programming for a modern UK audience. The channel was named Channel of the Year at the 2007 Broadcast Awards.

tvguide.programme_description: Quiz in which contestants try to score as few points as possible by plumbing the depths of their general knowledge to come up with the answers no-one else can think of. Presented by Alexander Armstrong and Richard Osman.
The latest national and international news stories from the BBC News team, followed by weather.
The latest news, sport and weather from London.
If it's got Britain talking then it will get talked about on The One Show. Presented by Matt Baker and Alex Jones.
Ian reaches breaking point and resorts to drastic measures. A jealous Babe takes matters into her own hands. Kush has a heart-to-heart with Shabnam.

Hospital drama. It's the day of the wedding. Adele's world is rocked when she makes a startling discovery. Is it a case of cold feet when Jesse arrives at Holby on the day of the wedding? A betrayed Cara wants answers from her husband, undercover detective Jed.

Drama about a team of retired detectives investigating unsolved crimes. UCOS are threatened with closure following their perceived mishandling of the Henway case. Their final case begins with the bloody murder of a political activist 15 years ago at the Madhouse - a hub for people with mental health issues. Just as the team are getting somewhere, the order comes from above for Ted, Danny and Steve to cease the investigation. But in true UCOS spirit, the boys throw away the rulebook and uncover something much bigger than just a straightforward murder, involving some top officials, a multinational drugs company and signs of a massive cover-up. Danny and Fiona's relationship hangs in the balance as she must give an answer to the job offer in Aberdeen, and Sasha is pulled into a game of political cat and mouse as she realises UCOS are merely puppets in Cynthia's game.
The latest national and international news, with reports from BBC correspondents worldwide.
The latest news, sport and weather from London.

Panorama investigates sensational allegations of historical child abuse and murder by some of the most prominent people in Britain: a paedophile ring at the heart of the Establishment. Why were the allegations described by police as 'credible and true' with no hard evidence or corroboration? What role have senior politicians and the media played in promoting this story around the world? And what price will genuine victims of child abuse pay if it turns out not to be true?
tvguide.programme_name: The VIP Paedophile Ring: What's the Truth?

tvguide.programme_description: Celebrity genealogy series. Journalist Anita Rani never met her maternal grandfather Sant Singh - all she has been told is that he suffered terrible tragedy at the time of India's partition. Anita's mother also tells her that Sant had another wife and family before marrying Anita's grandmother. Armed with this knowledge, Anita travels to India to see if she can find out more about her grandfather's first family and discover what happened to them during Partition.
tvguide.programme_name: Who Do You Think You Are?

tvguide.programme_description: Detailed weather forecast.
BBC One joins the BBC's rolling news channel for a night of news, with bulletins on the hour and the headlines every 15 minutes.
The latest news, sport, business and weather from the BBC's Breakfast team.

Gloria Hunniford, Angela Rippon and Julia Somerville present the programme that battles to get viewers' problems resolved. As the team investigate whether we always get value for money, there's an exclusive peek at the tough tests designed to identify which products are the best to go for. Also, with hundreds of millions of batteries used in the UK every year, how can you tell which ones will last the longest, and could it be that it's cheaper ones that give the best overall value? Plus a big family day out accused of not living up to the hype, and an online dress shop whose frocks don't quite measure up.

Martin Roberts and Lucy Alexander visit a Victorian terrace in Manchester, a building in Maidstone, Kent, and a house in Devon. All of these properties have been sold at auction; Martin and Lucy find out who bought them, and what they paid when they went under the hammer.

A look at the work of high court enforcement officers, also known as sheriffs, as they strive to retrieve cash for members of the public that are owed money. Tempers flare when sheriffs Lawrence and Kev chase up a debt in a case involving a man with multiple names. A former gym instructor is owed wages by the gym he worked for. Lawrence goes to see if he can work out the situation. A remote-controlled-plane enthusiast wanted a bigger car to help with his hobby, but the one he bought wasn't all it was cracked up to be. Sheriffs Marc and Tony visit the garage that sold it to try and get him his money back. A photocopier wholesaler owes a substantial sum to a former employee. The boss is away, but that won't stop Lawrence and Kev going in search of their client's money.

Factual series discovering what becomes of everyday possessions like bicycles and laptops when they are stolen. Tracking technology reveals where stolen items are taken. Startling footage reveals the techniques used by a female thief on the loose in London who steals handbags from the unwary. Meanwhile, West Midlands Police track down a burglar who committed break-ins after his release from prison wearing a GPS-based ankle tag.

Antiques show. Two teams of married couples join Tim Wonnacott on a buying bonanza in Hungerford. The contestants are joined by experts Nick Hall and Kate Bateman. Both teams are in for a big surprise at the auction. Meanwhile, Tim tracks down a pair of ornate candlesticks that have an interesting past.
The latest national and international news stories from the BBC News team, followed by weather.
The latest news, sport and weather from London.

Drama series set in a health centre. Heston gets a reminder that appearances can be deceptive when an elderly vagrant gets into his car by mistake. Ayesha's threat to expose Hayden backfires, and Emma drops her bombshell on Howard.

Quiz show hosted by Shane Richie. An HR director, a taxi driver and a full-time mum who have never met before face a golden wall of cash worth £20,000 and try to hang onto as much of it as possible by correctly answering a series of questions.

Series in which prospective buyers are helped to find their dream home in the country. Jonnie Irwin joins the house hunt in East Anglia to help a young family in need of a country residence for a budget of 500,000 pounds. Plus Jonnie slips on his dancing shoes for a unique routine showcasing Suffolk's musical heritage.

Families swap homes with complete strangers to travel around the UK. House-proud couples from the Wirral and Lancashire try out a new way of life as they swap homes. But will they love or loathe the experience, and which pair will come out the winner?

Antiques experts travel across the country, competing to make a profit at auction. Thomas Plant and Mark Stacey are halfway through their road trip. They shop in Essex and Suffolk before making their way towards an auction in Cambridge.

Quiz in which contestants try to score as few points as possible by plumbing the depths of their general knowledge to come up with the answers no-one else can think of. Presented by Alexander Armstrong and Richard Osman.
The latest national and international news stories from the BBC News team, followed by weather.
The latest news, sport and weather from London.
If it's got Britain talking then it will get talked about on The One Show. Presented by Matt Baker and Alex Jones.

Amateur baking challenge. Only three of the original twelve bakers remain. Now they face their last three challenges to discover who will be crowned winner of The Great British Bake Off 2015. The signature challenge sees the finalists tackle enriched dough to create delicious filled iced buns. The technical requires them to conquer something they have all struggled with, and finally, for their last ever showstopper, they must make a classic British cake. Mary and Paul expect nothing short of perfection.
Drama. Gemma is determined to expose Simon at last and ensure that he loses everything. She'll stop at nothing to achieve her goal - and the consequences will be explosive.
The latest national and international news, with reports from BBC correspondents worldwide.
The latest news, sport and weather from London.

Sue Barker hosts the lighthearted sports quiz. Graeme Swann goes up against Phil Tufnell as a team captain. They are joined by England batsman Joe Root, world champion swimmer Keri-Anne Payne, 200m sprinter Christian Malcolm and Premier League striker Kevin Campbell.

Over one million people were given emergency food in Britain in 2014, and the numbers are growing. This programme follows the stories of some of the people who get help from Scotland's busiest foodbank in Dundee. These include Charlie, who is left with no money to buy food after being the victim of a robbery, and single dad Billy, who is forced to get help from the foodbank to feed his four-year-old son Jack after a long spell out of work.
Detailed weather forecast.
BBC One joins the BBC's rolling news channel for a night of news, with bulletins on the hour and the headlines every 15 minutes.
The latest news, sport, business and weather from the BBC's Breakfast team.

Gloria Hunniford, Angela Rippon and Julia Somerville present the programme that battles to get viewers' problems resolved. The team investigate complaints about big-name brands, including a sofa store whose new furniture didn't please one woman in the way she'd expected from the ads, and the high street pharmacies giving advice that isn't correct. Also, with more people reporting unexpectedly high charges for going online, the team unravels how much data you'll typically use on everyday tasks. Plus the gamers who claim hackers have found a way to order from their online accounts.

Property renovation series. Martin, Lucy and Dion meet investors who hope to make some money from property bought at auction. Dion talks to a science teacher doing up a house in Bury in Lancashire, Lucy visits a two-bedroom ground-floor flat in Grove Park in London bought by a furniture maker, and Martin falls in love with a cottage built in the 1820s in Butetown in Wales.

A look at the work of high court enforcement officers, also known as sheriffs, as they strive to retrieve cash for members of the public that are owed money. Squatters have taken over a building in south east London and the owner wants them removed. Tensions rise when the sheriffs are left with no choice but to force their way in. A south coast puppeteer bought a faulty van from a local garage who haven't given her her money back. It's up to sheriffs Lawrence and Kev to try and get it for her. Sheriffs Darryl and Mark are on the trail of a dentist who owes a colossal amount of money to dozens of different people. But if they want to get any payment, they've got to find him first. Sheriff Pete pays a repeat visit to a road services company who still haven't paid up the money they owe to an ex-employee.

Factual series discovering what becomes of everyday possessions like bicycles and laptops when they are stolen. Tracking technology reveals where stolen items are taken. A car is broken into and a smartphone stolen, with the thief tracked across the East End of London. Meanwhile, police and tracking officers corner a robber who steals a massive tractor and goes on the rampage in West Yorkshire.

Antiques challenge. The teams travel to the Isle of Anglesey in the hope of finding unusual items to take to auction. Tim Wonnacott presides as the red and blue teams battle it out, whilst receiving expert advice from Charlie Ross and Catherine Southon. Tim is also in Buckinghamshire to visit Waddesdon Manor.
The latest national and international news stories from the BBC News team, followed by weather.
The latest news, sport and weather from London.

Drama series set in a health centre. When Jimmi's teenage patient falls under suspicion after a theft from the Mill, he follows him to a squat where a bigger shock lies in store. Elsewhere, Howard tries to make sense of Emma's revelation, and Mrs Tembe has a brainwave.

Quiz show hosted by Shane Richie. A retired accountant, a science teacher and a PA who have never met before face a golden wall of cash worth £20,000 and try to hang onto as much of it as possible by correctly answering a series of questions.

Property series. Jonnie Irwin is in rural north Somerset, property shopping with a budget of £500,000 for an engaged couple in the throes of planning their wedding. Along the way, Jonnie explores one of the county's extraordinary cave systems.

Families swap homes with complete strangers to travel around the UK. A trio from Suffolk swap houses with a couple from West Sussex to test-drive each other's homes and lifestyles. But who will emerge the winner of the swap?

Antiques experts travel across the country, competing to make a profit at auction. Thomas Plant and Mark Stacey are on a roll as they hunt for antique treasure across East Anglia. Along the way, Thomas hears the inspiring story of a pioneering nurse, and Mark learns the incredible history of a Dunwich lost to the waves. Then they hit the road towards their penultimate auction in Norwich.

Quiz in which contestants try to score as few points as possible by plumbing the depths of their general knowledge to come up with the answers no-one else can think of. Presented by Alexander Armstrong and Richard Osman.
The latest national and international news stories from the BBC News team, followed by weather.
The latest news, sport and weather from London.
If it's got Britain talking then it will get talked about on The One Show. Presented by Matt Baker and Alex Jones.
Ian reels from seeing a ghost from the past, but the reunion takes a sudden turn. Elaine and Babe come to terms with recent events. Shabnam and Kush struggle to stay united.

The consumer series returns with a new presenting team. Sophie Raworth and Michelle Ackerley join Matt Allwright and Chris Hollins. Five high street retailers fall short in an investigation into the fitting of child car seats, an eye surgery firm refuses to keep promises to customers about aftercare, and the rogue gardeners who march old people to the bank are chased down by Matt Allwright.

Celebrity genealogy series. Actor and writer Mark Gatiss has always had a love of storytelling and a passion for the ghastly and ghoulish but has always wondered where it comes from. So when he discovers that his mother's side of the family goes back five generations to the wilds of Northern Ireland, his imagination is awakened. Mark travels to Ireland, where he untangles a tale of rags to riches and finds out that his family were storytellers and - allegedly - vampire slayers!
tvguide.programme_name: Who Do You Think You Are?

tvguide.programme_description: The latest national and international news, with reports from BBC correspondents worldwide.
The latest news, sport and weather from London.

David Dimbleby presents topical debate from Leicester. On the panel are Conservative employment minister Priti Patel MP, leader of the Liberal Democrats Tim Farron MP, deputy leader of the SNP Stewart Hosie MP, Labour's shadow energy secretary Lisa Nandy MP and Times columnist Melanie Phillips.
Andrew Neil reviews the political week.
Detailed weather forecast.
BBC One joins the BBC's rolling news channel for a night of news, with bulletins on the hour and the headlines every 15 minutes.
The latest news, sport, business and weather from the BBC's Breakfast team.

Gloria Hunniford, Angela Rippon and Julia Somerville present the programme that battles to get viewers' problems resolved. The team investigate fake promises and products that could end up costing more than just money - with shocking lab tests revealing why counterfeit cosmetics aren't always the harmless bargain they might appear. Also, how fraudsters behind the type of accident scam driving up the cost of car insurance had their plans scuppered, and the team expose bogus celebrity endorsements that tempt you into handing over cash for something you may later regret. Plus the fake blender cashing in on one of the latest must-have gadgets - what are the risks if you accidentally buy the wrong one?

Martin Roberts and Lucy Alexander visit a terraced house in Gateshead, a flat in Shepherd's Bush, London, and a two-bed mid-terrace in Preston, Lancashire. All of these properties have been sold at auction; Martin and Lucy find out who bought them, and what they paid when they went under the hammer.

A look at the work of high court enforcement officers, also known as sheriffs, as they strive to retrieve cash for members of the public that are owed money. Sheriffs Tom and Craig visit a Coventry convenience store in an attempt to clear a big debt. But when Tom is confronted and prevented from removing goods, the law steps in. Can the sheriffs get any of the money owed? Sheriffs Lawrence and Kev are called to a well-known London pub. It's been occupied by squatters, barricaded and booby trapped. Can they get themselves in and the squatters out? Sheriffs Marc and Kev visit a south London garage to try to get money back from a disgruntled former business associate. There's a trip to a Midlands security firm for sheriffs Darryl and Mark, on behalf of a former employee owed money.

Factual series discovering what becomes of everyday possessions like bicycles and laptops when they are stolen. Tracking technology reveals where stolen items are taken. A south London thief makes off with a camera, unaware that he's being tracked! Meanwhile, a police officer turned pet detective recovers a beloved family terrier stolen from outside a post office.

Antiques challenge. Tim Wonnacott and the teams are in Stafford in search of bargains that will hopefully turn a profit at auction. At the fair, a team of steampunks take on two friends with a penchant for old-fashioned attire. While the reds rely on the expertise of Colin Young and the blues team up with Kate Bliss, Tim finds a rare toy that has a lovely ring to it.
The latest national and international news stories from the BBC News team, followed by weather.
The latest news, sport and weather from London.

Drama series set in a health centre. At Mrs Tembe's meditation session, some struggle to find the answers they seek, but Emma makes a big decision about the future. Elsewhere, Howard shocks Daniel with an admission about his past and is left unsure about what he wants.

Quiz show hosted by Shane Richie. A school sports manager, a retired English teacher and an assistant brand manager who have never met before face a golden wall of cash worth £20,000 and try to hang onto as much of it as possible by correctly answering a series of questions.

Series in which prospective buyers are helped to find their dream home in the country. Jules Hudson travels to north Devon to help a military couple who are looking to put down roots in the countryside for a budget of 500,000 pounds. Plus Jules catches up with a pair of escapees who found their dream home in a previous series.

Families swap homes with complete strangers to travel around the UK. Couples from South Yorkshire and Devon put their homes and lifestyles under the microscope as they exchange properties. But who will be crowned the winner?

Antiques experts travel across the country, competing to make a profit at auction. It is the last leg for antiques experts Mark Stacey and Thomas Plant as they travel through Norfolk. With less than £30 separating them, the pressure is on as they head to their final auction in Oakham, Rutland.

Quiz in which contestants try to score as few points as possible by plumbing the depths of their general knowledge to come up with the answers no-one else can think of. Presented by Alexander Armstrong and Richard Osman.
The latest national and international news stories from the BBC News team, followed by weather.
The latest news, sport and weather from London.
If it's got Britain talking then it will get talked about on The One Show. Presented by Alex Jones.

Rob Brydon, Lee Mack and David Mitchell return for an episode of previously unseen material from the hit comedy panel show. Over the course of the show, a stellar cast of celebrity guests reveal amazing stories about themselves, some of which are true and some of which are not. The aim of the game is to fool the opposition into mistaking fact for fiction and fiction for fact. Amongst the guests are Claudia Winkleman, Miles Jupp, Bob Mortimer, Jo Brand, Adil Ray, Kirsty Wark, Gareth Malone, Micky Flanagan, Amanda Abbington, Kian Egan, Carol Vorderman, Rhod Gilbert, Phill Jupitus, Fiona Bruce, Ray Mears, Adam Buxton, Bruno Tonioli, Mel Giedroyc, Hal Cruttenden, Steve Jones and Emilia Fox.
Emotions are high in Albert Square when Ian demands answers from those closest to him. At the Vic, Jay's birthday celebrations take a turn.

Granville's big ambitions to open his very own coffee shop cause quite a stir in the neighbourhood. Mrs Dawlish, a snobbish local, pays a visit and cannot believe such a corner shop still exists - can Granville find a clever way to make some money from her? Meanwhile Eric looks after his depressed brother-in-law all day.
The satirical news quiz returns. Regular team captains Paul Merton and Ian Hislop are joined by guest host Kathy Burke and guest panellists Charlie Brooker and Nish Kumar.
tvguide.programme_name: Have I Got News for You

tvguide.programme_description: Family sitcom set in the 1970s. It's Valentine's Day on Jessop Square, and everyone is opening their cards. Emma has received one for the first time ever and she resolves to find out who sent it to her. Brenda opens some post that has been lying about for weeks, only to discover that her driving test is in two days' time - even though she cannot drive. Brenda begins her lessons but at the first attempt manages to finish off Tony's old car. Meanwhile, Jenny is convinced that Tim is going to use the most romantic day of the year to propose.
The latest national and international news, with reports from BBC correspondents worldwide.
The latest news, sport and weather from London.

Talk show. Together on Graham's sofa are Hollywood legend Meryl Streep and Oscar-nominated British actress Carey Mulligan, co-starring in new British drama Suffragette, and Academy Award winner Nicole Kidman, currently winning rave reviews on the West End stage in Photograph 51.

Series in which comedian Romesh Ranganathan is sent by his mother on a ramshackle odyssey around his parents' homeland of Sri Lanka as he attempts to connect with his roots. Romesh is sent to Batticloa to meet his Uncle Ragu who has been given a mandate from Romesh's mum. They visit the village where his mum grew up and Romesh is slightly taken aback to discover that not only is everyone living there related to him, they're related to each other too. Ragu and Romesh join a 200km barefoot pilgrimage to Kataragama, where there is a holy festival. Romesh finds himself surrounded by people piercing odd and disturbing body parts, and meets a man possessed by a snake who he thinks might be able to fix his lazy eye. However, Romesh is quickly leading Ragu astray - persuading him to desert their pilgrimage after an hour and questioning how good an idea it is to get his mouth speared together at the festival.

Comic drama based on actual events. Chance brings Beth to work for Dink, whose Las Vegas gambling business seeks to make money on the margins between betting odds. But she has the misfortune of being mistrusted by Dink's shrewish wife Tulip and then of having the temptation to try her luck with roguish 'Rosie' operating illegally in New York.
Detailed weather forecast.
BBC One joins the BBC's rolling news channel for a night of news, with bulletins on the hour and the headlines every 15 minutes.
The latest news, sport, business and weather from the BBC's Breakfast team.

James Martin presents the weekly cookery programme with help from top chefs Jose Pizarro and Shivi Ramoutar. With great moments from the BBC food archive, including clips from Rick Stein, Mary Berry, the Hairy Bikers and Antonio Carluccio. Actress Katherine Parkinson faces her food heaven or food hell. Wine expert Jane Parkinson chooses wine to match the dishes in the studio.

Dan Walker looks ahead to the weekend's football action, which focuses on the final two rounds of qualifying for the 2016 European Championship. England qualified in September, while Wales go into their last two matches needing just one point to confirm a place in France. A first European Championship beckons for Northern Ireland, but things look more difficult for the Republic of Ireland and Scotland. All in all, plenty for Dan and his guests to get their teeth into.
The latest national and international news from the BBC.

Suzi Perry hosts live coverage of qualifying for the Russian Grand Prix from Sochi. Reigning F1 champion Lewis Hamilton has won more races than any other driver this season, and he will be aiming to finish on pole again in Sochi. The Briton dominated proceedings last year, winning the race proper after also topping the times in qualifying.

Antiques challenge. Four intrepid teams take part in a one-hour bumper Bargain Hunt special. Experts Kate Bliss and David Harper guide the teams towards the best buys at Derby University, while Tim Wonnacott pays a visit to Hatfield House in Herefordshire.

Programme looking back over the bakes of the 2014 series, from Luis's amazing 3D biscuit scene, via the technically challenging schichttorte to Ian's binning of his baked alaska. The bakers from 2014 reveal what they really thought about their time in the tent, share their memories and catch viewers up with what they have been doing since.
tvguide.programme_name: The Great British Bake Off Class of 2014

tvguide.programme_description: Property show. With a budget of £250,000, Aled Jones helps some young newlyweds hoping to buy their first home in Lincolnshire. During his journey around the county, Aled goes on a very unique delivery round with a community-based baking business.
The latest national and international news from the BBC.
The latest news, sport and weather from London.

Alexander Armstrong and Richard Osman present a special celebrity writers edition of the general knowledge quiz in which four teams try to come up with the answers that no-one else could think of. Featuring Germaine Greer and Kathy Lette, Mark Billingham and Val McDermid, Mark Watson and Ian McMillan, and Freya North and Tony Parsons.

Celebrity dance contest. It's Saturday night at the movies as Strictly celebrates some of the biggest films in history. We are now down to 14 couples and every one of them has to deliver an amazing routine to a classic movie track stay in the competition. Who will get into character and deliver award-winning performances, and who will be flops at the box office? Tess Daly and Claudia Winkleman host an evening full of sparkling moves, iconic songs and plenty of surprises.

Sci-fi drama. On a remote army outpost, a fearsome alien warlord called the Fisher King sets in motion a twisted plan to ensure his own survival. The ripples will be felt around the universe. Is this chain of events inevitable? And can the Doctor do the unthinkable?
Hospital drama. Cal's back on an even keel. Can things only get better?

The National Lottery Live presented by Gaby Roslin, including the Lotto and Thunderball draws. Plus two exclusive music and dance performances by four Lottery-funded projects from across the UK. Sing With Us and Dance4 perform a one minute version of Karl Jenkins's Adiemus. Plus a performance by Du Dance and Audio Active.
The latest national and international news from the BBC.

Comedy series about a meddling market stall holder and matriarch. The family celebrate the baptism of Dermot and Maria's triplets with a party. An unwitting Agnes and Winnie, however, are put under the spell of the hypnotist booked to provide the entertainment. Agnes's kitchen is falling apart, but she soon has other priorities when son Mark delivers some upsetting news.

Swashbuckling adventure. In the fourth instalment of the series, Jack Sparrow finds himself on the hunt to find the Fountain of Youth as he is held captive on Blackbeard's ship. Having bumped into a former flame who lures him on board, Jack finds himself battling zombies and encountering mermaids as he tries to defeat his arch-enemy once and for all.
tvguide.programme_name: Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides

tvguide.programme_description: Detailed weather forecast.
BBC One joins the BBC's rolling news channel for a night of news, with bulletins on the hour and the headlines every 15 minutes.
The latest news, sport, business and weather from the BBC's Breakfast team.
Interviews with key newsmakers and cultural figures, and a look at what is happening in the world this week.
Sian Williams and guests debate the moral and spiritual issues of the day.

Suzi Perry introduces live coverage of the Russian Grand Prix, the 15th of the 19 races on the 2015 Formula 1 calendar. Lewis Hamilton won the inaugural contest last year - it was his 31st F1 race victory, equalling Nigel Mansell's record for a British driver - and also clinched the constructors' championship for the Mercedes team.
Andrew Neil and Tim Donovan with the latest political news, interviews and debate.

Amateur baking challenge. Only three of the original twelve bakers remain. Now they face their last three challenges to discover who will be crowned winner of The Great British Bake Off 2015. The signature challenge sees the finalists tackle enriched dough to create delicious filled iced buns. The technical requires them to conquer something they have all struggled with, and finally, for their last ever showstopper, they must make a classic British cake. Mary and Paul expect nothing short of perfection.

Property show where people search for their dream house in the country. Nicki Chapman helps a couple of equestrian enthusiasts swap suburban life in Farnborough, Hampshire, for a new rural existence in Somerset. Their budget of £600,000 needs to secure not only a country home but also land for their horses. Away from the house hunting, Nicki wades through mud as she encounters an age-old fishing technique.
Jeremy Vine presents audience views on BBC TV over the week. Send comments in to pov@bbc.co.UK or to Points of View, BBC Northern Ireland, Belfast BT2 8HQ.

Springwatch presenter Michaela Strachan makes an appeal on behalf of Breast Cancer Now, the UK's largest breast cancer research charity. Last year, Michaela was diagnosed with breast cancer, so she knows only too well what it's like to live with this disease which will affect one in eight women in the UK in their lifetime. The film features Connie, who was diagnosed with breast cancer aged 23. Following a mastectomy, Connie found that the cancer had spread to her liver. We also meet Jim, who lost his wife Moira to secondary breast cancer. Breast Cancer Now believe that the key to a world where no one dies of breast cancer is research into the disease. That's why Breast Cancer Now funds researchers like Dr Paul Shore at the University of Manchester (also featured), who has identified a gene that causes breast cancer cells to spread.

Sally Magnusson joins Lord of the Rings fans at a Tolkien festival, David Grant visits the home of William Blake, and historian Richard Taylor is at Jane Austen's church. Plus some great hymns to sing along with.
The latest national and international news stories from the BBC News team.
The latest news, sport and weather from London.

Matt Baker and Helen Skelton are in Cheshire, where Matt is at the magnificent Lyme Park, hoping for a glimpse of one of nature's most exciting spectacles - the annual red deer rut. He joins photographer Gary Lomas at dawn, and together they try to capture this magnificent event. Matt also meets a former TV actor who gave up the limelight for a life in the country as a trainee National Trust ranger. Helen is out at dusk with the conservationists on a bat hunt at Tatton Park. She also looks at the rising popularity of gin and meets the family firm making bespoke gin from foraged plants. James Wong is at Norton Priory - home to the National Quince Collection. He learns of the important work being done to preserve one of our oldest fruits and tries his hand at making quince jelly. Also in this programme, Adam heads to Devon to look at Dartmoor sheep and ponies, and Tom Heap looks at the reasons why mental health issues such as depression are a particular problem in the farming community.

Celebrity dance contest. It's time for another couple to leave the floor as the movie weekend builds to its finale. The only sequel in Strictly is the dreaded dance-off, and no-one wants to find themselves in the bottom two. And Italian singing sensation Andrea Bocelli performs a classic track from a Hollywood blockbuster.

Fiona Bruce presents from the Royal William Yard in Plymouth. Finds include a pair of doorknobs said to have belonged to Lord Nelson, though militaria specialist Graham Lay has doubts about them, and a psychedelic painting of a band that played at Woodstock. Jewellery specialist John Benjamin marvels at a huge diamond necklace the length of skipping rope, while the team are also impressed by a chess set made from parts of the aircraft carrier HMS Ark Royal, a winged armchair that has travelled from Vermont, USA, and a rare Japanese bronze vase that had been languishing in a Yorkshire garden.

Psychological crime drama. The discovery of a new victim carries a haunting message for Claire - her old shoulder number left on the body. It can't be dismissed as coincidence - someone wants Claire's attention, and she can't run any longer. When she has to return to Manchester, John tries to use the investigation to reignite an old flame, causing Norrie to fear for his relationship with Claire. As she is drawn into the task of identifying the bodies, Claire's desire for justice supersedes her fear of violence. Determined to fight for the women she let down, Claire plunges recklessly into the case, only realising too late that her own life is directly threatened too.
The latest national and international news, with reports from BBC correspondents worldwide.
The latest news, sport and weather from London.

Sir Alex Ferguson is one of the greatest leaders this country has ever produced. He was the mastermind of one of Britain's leading brands. Not a soft drink or a smart phone, but a football club: Manchester United. In 26 years, Sir Alex transformed United into a multimillion-pound global business, picking up every single domestic trophy there is in football along the way. His leadership is unique in the history of world football. During this extraordinary encounter, BBC political editor Nick Robinson gets up close and personal with Sir Alex and uncovers the secrets of his success. Sir Alex shares his unique insights on leadership that speak to everyone, revealing how he stayed at the top of his profession for so long and, crucially, how best to motivate, discipline and inspire people. Featuring contributions from Cristiano Ronaldo, Tony Blair, General Sir Michael Jackson, Lord Sugar, Ryan Giggs, Rio Ferdinand, Sir Michael Moritz, Jose Mourinho and Professor Anita Elberse.
tvguide.programme_name: Sir Alex Ferguson: Secrets of Success

tvguide.programme_description: When Wayne Rooney scored against Switzerland at Wembley in September 2015, he broke Sir Bobby Charlton's England goal-scoring record. But who is the real Wayne Rooney, off the pitch and away from the glare of the media spotlight? For the first time, he has allowed a television production team, as well as BBC football presenter Gary Lineker, unique access to his life with wife Coleen and their two sons, Kai and Klay. Featuring extensive interviews with Rooney himself, plus Coleen Rooney, Wayne's parents, David Beckham and Real Madrid star Cristiano Ronaldo, along with a host of figures from the world of football.
tvguide.programme_name: Rooney: The Man Behind the Goals

tvguide.programme_description: Detailed weather forecast.
BBC One joins the BBC's rolling news channel for a night of news, with bulletins on the hour and the headlines every 15 minutes.
The latest news, sport, business and weather from the BBC's Breakfast team.

Gloria Hunniford, Angela Rippon and Julia Somerville present the programme that battles to get viewers' problems resolved. In this episode they unpick new and all-too-plausible scams that leave people thousands of pounds out of pocket, including a would-be suitor charming his targets out of their savings. Plus, a shameless con that saw expensive goods stolen right from under a charity's nose, the man renting out flats he doesn't even own, and the truth about apparently separate websites with more in common than expected. Also, advice for avoiding fraudsters, and the Rip Off Britain Pop-up Shop opens its doors in the West Midlands.

Martin Roberts and Lucy Alexander visit a house in Stoke-on-Trent, a three-bed mid-terrace in Swanscombe, Kent, and a commercial property in Mid Glamorgan. All of these properties have been sold at auction; Martin and Lucy find out who bought them, and what they paid when they went under the hammer.

A look at the work of high court enforcement officers, also known as sheriffs, as they strive to retrieve cash for members of the public that are owed money. When a couple arranged to have their spectacular Indian wedding filmed, they never dreamed it would take over 18 months to see the disappointing results. They were so unhappy, they won a High Court judgment against the video company. It's crowbars at dawn when sheriffs Lawrence and Kev go to get the couple their money from the reluctant business owner. A Cambridgeshire garage owner sold a car with multiple problems and failed to give the buyer her money back. Can sheriffs Darryl and Mark get her what's rightfully hers, or will they be forced to take more drastic action? Sheriff Pete pops into a camper van company. Can he get the disgruntled former customer back the money he's owed?

Dom Littlewood looks at clever new methods that the police and the public are using to catch crooks red-handed. A woman creeping across a disabled man's floor horrifies his family, and there's a rat on the loose in a restaurant - but there's a twist to the tale.
Antiques dealer Tim Wonnacott gives two teams of amateur collectors an hour at an antiques fair in which to acquire the best bargains possible on a limited budget.
The latest national and international news stories from the BBC News team, followed by weather.
The latest news, sport and weather from London.

It Starts with the Shoes. Drama series set in a health centre. Karen helps a man to find some gorgeous high heels, but are they really a present for his sister? Meanwhile, Emma has decided what she wants to do about the baby, and Ayesha has her own decision to make about Hayden.
Gabby Logan takes charge of the quiz where contestants need brainpower and ball skills to win big. Who will be the high roller and who will push themselves over The Edge?

Series in which prospective buyers are helped to find their dream home in the country. Denise Nurse helps a family with a budget of £400,000 find a country home in the expensive county of Surrey. Away from the house hunt, Denise takes a tour of the Royal Horticultural Society's Gardens in Wisley.

Families swap homes with complete strangers to travel around the UK. Couples from Kent and Gloucestershire, and their dogs, put their homes and lifestyle under the microscope as they exchange properties. But will they love or loathe their adventure, and how will they score the experience?
Antiques experts Anita Manning and James Lewis start out in Deddington, Oxfordshire on the first leg of their journey, before crossing into Hertfordshire for the auction in St Albans.

Quiz in which contestants try to score as few points as possible by plumbing the depths of their general knowledge to come up with the answers no-one else can think of. Presented by Alexander Armstrong and Richard Osman.
The latest national and international news stories from the BBC News team, followed by weather.
The latest news, sport and weather from London.
If it's got Britain talking then it will get talked about on The One Show. Presented by Matt Baker and Alex Jones.
The programme investigates the hidden dangers associated with breast milk bought over the internet. And the Hillingdon village coping with coachloads of refugees.
Kathy attempts to build bridges with her family, but how will they react? Kush turns to Masood for advice, but Shabnam later drops a bombshell.

As the UK's imprisonment rate remains the highest in western Europe, Panorama joins Michael Gove - the man in charge of British prisons - on a fact-finding mission in Texas. 'Hang 'em high' Texas is not the first place you might look for lessons in criminal justice - they execute more people and lock up more offenders than anywhere else in America. But now this conservative state is the unlikely centre of a rehabilitation-led revolution in prison reform that's sweeping through the US. Crime is down, prisoner numbers have fallen and, on top of this, they have cut costs. Are there valuable lessons to be learned here, and are UK politicians really ready to dole out some Texan justice?

Featuring the latest crime investigations, news and appeals. Featuring the latest crime investigations, news and appeals. On the eve of the release of new statistics expected to show a rise in hate crime offences, Crimewatch enlists the help of some familiar BBC faces to explore the problem and its shocking impact on victims. Also, an insight from senior detectives into how they prove someone has been killed even when they can't find a body. Jane Harrison disappeared from her north London home in 1995. She has never been found, but her partner Kevin Doherty was shown to be guilty of killing her, thanks - in part - to the use of mobile phone cell site analysis to unpick his lies. Plus, the usual round-up of crimes caught on CCTV and a fresh collection of wanted faces.
The latest national and international news, with reports from BBC correspondents worldwide.
The latest news, sport and weather from London.
The team is back live with the latest developments on the cases featured during the evening's main programme.
Extended version of the satirical news quiz. Kathy Burke hosts, with regular team captains Paul Merton and Ian Hislop and guest panellists Charlie Brooker and Nish Kumar.
tvguide.programme_name: Have I Got a Bit More News for You

tvguide.programme_description: Talk show. Together on Graham's sofa are Hollywood legend Meryl Streep and Oscar-nominated British actress Carey Mulligan, co-starring in new British drama Suffragette, and Academy Award winner Nicole Kidman, currently winning rave reviews on the West End stage in Photograph 51.
Detailed weather forecast.

The latest news, sport, business and weather from the BBC's Breakfast team.

Gloria Hunniford, Angela Rippon and Julia Somerville present the programme that battles to get viewers' problems resolved. The team reveal how to become more online-savvy and avoid being stung by internet fraudsters or companies that are not what they seem. An experiment reveals just how easy it is to piece together personal details from even the most basic clues online - and just how far those details may then travel. Plus the team unpick why it is that online ads can so accurately reflect genuine interest, meet a woman who has lost out to a scamster taking advantage of her 'friends' on social media, and uncover how to spot which websites claiming to be based in the UK are in fact nothing of the kind.

Property renovation series. Former Manchester United footballer Dion Dublin has traded the theatre of dreams for the world of property developing to join Martin Roberts and Lucy Alexander on Homes under the Hammer. Between them, the trio look at a terraced house in Burnley, a detached house in Liverpool and a bungalow in Derby. But will any of the properties make money for their new owners?

A look at the work of high court enforcement officers, also known as sheriffs, as they strive to retrieve cash for members of the public that are owed money. A central London guitar school sold a customer's classic guitar and then kept her money. Can the sheriffs change their tune? A ski instructor wasn't paid over £600 of wages by the holiday company he worked for. Sheriffs Lawrence and Kev go in search of what he's owed. A trainee electrician bought a car which turned out to have seriously faulty locks. He had to shell out for the repair. Can Lawrence and Kev get him his money back? A parking warden is owed thousands by the company that dismissed him. Sheriff Pete goes to collect the debt.

Dom Littlewood looks at clever new methods that the police and the public are using to catch crooks red-handed. A robber swings a homemade weapon at two friends, and a gang of sneaky crooks target the elderly in Kent.

Antiques show. A pair of policemen take on some self-named glamorous grannies. The teams are expertly assisted by Catherine Southon and Thomas Plant as they hunt for bargains in the antiques centres of Lewes. Presenter Tim Wonnacott visits an eighteenth-century watermill with an intriguing history.
The latest national and international news stories from the BBC News team, followed by weather.
The latest news, sport and weather from London.
Girl about Town. Drama series set in a health centre. Sid helps a blogger come to terms with who she is. Meanwhile, Ayesha has a confession to make - and so does Rob.
Gabby Logan takes charge of the quiz where contestants need brainpower and ball skills to win big. Who will be the high roller and who will push themselves over The Edge?

Property series. Nicki Chapman helps a campervan-loving couple with £400,000 find a perfect rural property within range of the Peak District. Along the way, Nicki turns her hand to some unique woodcraft with Britain's last traditional bowl turner.

Families swap homes with complete strangers to travel around the UK. House-proud couples from Dorset and Devon try out a new way of life. But with each couple scoring their experience, who will be the winner?

Antiques experts Anita Manning and James Lewis begin in the London district of Wimbledon, before travelling through Molesey in Surrey and then heading for their auction near the town of Alresford in Hampshire.

Quiz in which contestants try to score as few points as possible by plumbing the depths of their general knowledge to come up with the answers no-one else can think of. Presented by Alexander Armstrong and Richard Osman.
The latest national and international news stories from the BBC News team, followed by weather.

Ben comes face to face with a person from the past and quickly sees their true colours. Shabnam's plan begins to fall apart, but is it for the best? Two residents find themselves taking things to the next level.

Hospital drama. Mo is knocked for six when her old friend Sorcia turns up with Mo's surrogate son, William. Sublimating her distress over the break-up of her marriage, Cara defies Raf to help a vulnerable patient. Jesse strives to prove himself as a surgeon when he shadows Sacha for the day.

Drama series. John River is a respected police officer haunted by the murder victims whose secrets he must uncover. Struggling to come to terms with the recent loss of a close colleague, River chases a potential suspect across London, with tragic consequences. In his fragile mental state, he comes under increasing pressure both from the press and within the police force as calls for his dismissal grow. Meanwhile, the mother of a murdered teenager is growing increasingly desperate - the boyfriend has confessed but no body has been found, and she blames River for failing to make good on his promise to find her daughter.
The latest national and international news, with reports from BBC correspondents worldwide.
The latest news, sport and weather from London.

Brett Nielsen has no arms because his mum took thalidomide. Film-maker Roger Graef's 1965 documentary One of Them is Brett was an extraordinary story about a spirited four-year-old's fight for identity and survival. His parents sold up and moved from Australia to Britain to get Brett the medical help he couldn't get there. Fifty years later, whatever happened to him? Roger has tracked him down in this follow-up film which tells the story of Brett's life since he was a child. Brett's now a musician, record producer, businessman and a loving single dad with three ex-wives. And he's in love yet again. It's a film about passion, optimism and fun, a story of triumph over adversity.
tvguide.programme_name: Brett: A Life with No Arms

tvguide.programme_description: Celebrity genealogy series. Actor and writer Mark Gatiss has always had a love of storytelling and a passion for the ghastly and ghoulish but has always wondered where it comes from. So when he discovers that his mother's side of the family goes back five generations to the wilds of Northern Ireland, his imagination is awakened. Mark travels to Ireland, where he untangles a tale of rags to riches and finds out that his family were storytellers and - allegedly - vampire slayers!
tvguide.programme_name: Who Do You Think You Are?

Gloria Hunniford, Angela Rippon and Julia Somerville present the programme that battles to get viewers' problems resolved. The team explore the disastrous fallout some viewers have had from extreme weather. A sinkhole that dramatically appeared in one family's back garden reveals an unexpected gap in what is covered by home insurance, and the team get to the bottom of why homeowners nowhere near water are being told they are suddenly at greater risk of flooding. Plus, the town where residents have been priced out of buying the protection they need the most, one couple's two-year battle to prove their home was damaged by a storm, more problems solved at the Rip Off Britain Pop-Up Shop, and unmissable tips and advice from the programme's experts.

Martin Roberts and Lucy Alexander visit a cottage in Cornwall, a flat in London and a terrace in Yorkshire. All of these properties have been sold at auction; Martin and Lucy find out who bought them, and what they paid when they went under the hammer.

A look at the work of high court enforcement officers, also known as sheriffs, as they strive to retrieve cash for members of the public that are owed money. A pub landlord paid £10,000 for wind turbines on the roof of his Dartmoor pub that didn't work. The sheriffs go in search of his money. An Oxfordshire car mechanic fixed a rental company's van, but they refused to pay him. Sheriffs Lawrence and Kev go to find out why. A civil servant bought a top-of-the-range car as a retirement present, but it ended up costing him over £1700 for major repairs. Can the sheriffs get his money back? Lawrence and Kev pay a visit to a Kent convenience store on the trail of a substantial debt.

Dom Littlewood looks at clever new methods that the police and the public are using to catch crooks red-handed. One man and his dog face a gang of thieves, and a shopkeeper is confronted by a man with a knife.

Antiques show. Tim Wonnacott and the team have landed at the East of England Showground. The red and blue teams do battle around the hundreds of stalls and are joined by experts David Harper and Kate Bliss. Tim comes across an interesting find at the fair and there are some highs and lows at the saleroom.
The latest national and international news stories from the BBC News team, followed by weather.

Drama series set in a health centre. Al gets caught up with a gang from the Churchill Estate. Meanwhile, Ayesha's career is at stake thanks to Hayden's actions.
Gabby Logan takes charge of the quiz where contestants need brainpower and ball skills to win big. Who will be the high roller and who will push themselves over The Edge?
Property series. Jules Hudson is in South Wales with a couple who have a £350,000 budget to buy a home in the country. Plus, Jules is given special access to the Royal Mint.

Families swap homes with complete strangers to travel around the UK. A mum and daughter from West Sussex swap their watery home with a couple from south Gloucestershire. But will they enjoy exchanging lifestyles? And which duo will be the winners?

Antiques experts Anita Manning and James Lewis begin this leg of their journey near Lacock in Wiltshire, before travelling through Bath, Frome and Swindon and heading for the auction in Cirencester, Gloucestershire.
